    <div class="tab-pane fade" id="profile">
        <h2>Key project Achievements - Kaduna</h2>
        <div class="col-md-12">
            <hr />
            <blockquote>
                <p>
                    Following the outcome of the survey conducted by IITA on Aflatoxin contamination of food and feeds across the country in 2009 which found Kaduna State to fall within high risks of Aflatoxin infection with almost 25% of maize in the State been unsafe for human/livestock consumption, Kaduna CADP entered into collaboration with IITA for the demonstration and adoption of Aflasafe maize production. By 2013, a 90% reduction in maize Aflatoxin had been recorded in the State through the collaboration and for the farmers, that achievement meant a substantial improvement in quality and marketability of their maize output.
                </p>
            </blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p>
                    Aflasafe maize farmers were subsequently linked with up-takers (NALMACO, Ugo Farm, Dar-al-green, Grand Cereal Company & Springfield) for assured market access for Aflasafe maize, and
                    Between 2011 and 2014, about 52 maize CIGs were able to record sales of about 5,863 metric tonnes of maize from Giwa and Kubau maize belt alone. Through inter State linkage also, Aflasafe maize producers in Kaduna were able to gain access to markets in Enugu and Lagos States with sale of 90 tons of Aflasafe maize to Sunchi Integrated Farm Ltd, the new hatchery in Enugu at a premium price of N52,000/ton and 240 metric tonnes of maize sold to poultry farmers in Lagos and to Lagos State Agricultural Input Supply Agency from 2013-2014. Also, twenty six (26) CIGs comprising 436 aflasafe maize producers were linked to Stanbic IBTC Bank which provided them with credit facilities amounting to about N355,168,384.00 for Aflasafe Maize production
                </p>
            </blockquote>
        </div>


